  "ABW:aruba": "A constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, Aruba gained separate status from the Netherlands Antilles in 1986.",
  // AFG
  "AFG:badakhshan": "Remote northeastern province famous for its lapis lazuli mines, among the world's oldest, continuously mined for over 6,000 years.",
  "AFG:takhar": "Northern province whose capital Taloqan served as a key Northern Alliance base during the 1990s civil war and 2001 campaign.",
  "AFG:kunduz": "Northern agricultural hub known for cotton production and site of a major 2015 Taliban offensive that briefly seized the city.",
  "AFG:balkh": "Home to Mazar-i-Sharif, site of the famous Blue Mosque (Shrine of Hazrat Ali), one of Afghanistan's holiest and most visited landmarks.",
  "AFG:jowzjan": "Northern province rich in natural gas reserves, with major fields around Sheberghan that have been exploited since the Soviet era.",
  "AFG:faryab": "Northwestern province with a large Uzbek population; its capital Maymana is a historic Silk Road trading town.",
  "AFG:badghis": "Northwestern province bordering Turkmenistan, one of Afghanistan's most food-insecure regions due to recurrent drought.",
  "AFG:herat": "Western province whose capital Herat is celebrated for its 15th-century Timurid architecture, including the Great Mosque and Friday Mosque minarets.",
  "AFG:nimruz": "Afghanistan's most sparsely populated province; it contains the ruins of the ancient city of Zaranj, now the provincial capital on the Iranian border.",
  "AFG:farah": "Large southwestern province known for its pomegranate orchards and site of one of the deadliest U.S. airstrikes of the Afghan war in 2009.",
  "AFG:kunar": "Rugged eastern province bordering Pakistan, site of the Battle of Wanat (2008) and extensive U.S. special operations activity due to insurgent infiltration routes.",
  "AFG:nuristan": "Remote mountain province whose isolated inhabitants converted to Islam only in 1896; it preserves distinct wooden architecture and pre-Islamic cultural traditions.",
  "AFG:nangarhar": "Eastern province whose capital Jalalabad links Kabul to the Khyber Pass; it is one of Afghanistan's largest opium poppy-producing regions.",
  "AFG:khost": "Southeastern province bordering Pakistan known for the CIA Forward Operating Base Chapman, site of a deadly 2009 suicide bombing that killed seven CIA officers.",
  "AFG:paktia": "Southeastern Pashtun heartland province; its capital Gardez was a key Soviet stronghold and later saw major coalition operations including Operation Anaconda (2002).",
  "AFG:paktika": "Remote southeastern province bordering Pakistan, one of Afghanistan's poorest, and heavily affected by the devastating 2022 earthquake that killed over 1,000 people.",
  "AFG:zabul": "Southern province widely regarded as a Taliban stronghold; its capital Qalat sits along the ancient route connecting Kandahar to Ghazni.",
  "AFG:kandahar": "Afghanistan's second-largest city and spiritual birthplace of the Taliban, historically significant as the first capital under Ahmad Shah Durrani in the 18th century.",
  "AFG:helmand": "Southern province producing the majority of Afghanistan's opium and heroin; the Helmand River valley irrigation scheme was a major 1950s U.S. development project.",
  "AFG:urozgan": "Central-southern province that is the birthplace of Taliban founder Mullah Omar, and site of sustained Dutch and Australian NATO operations after 2006.",
  "AFG:ghazni": "Central province whose capital Ghazni was the 10th–11th century capital of the Ghaznavid Empire under Sultan Mahmud, a major center of Islamic culture.",
  "AFG:parwan": "Northern Kabul province containing Bagram Airfield, the largest U.S. military base in Afghanistan throughout the post-2001 conflict.",
  "AFG:kabul": "Capital province home to Kabul city, Afghanistan's largest city and political, economic, and cultural center, situated at roughly 1,800 m elevation.",
  "AFG:laghman": "Eastern province known for fertile river valleys producing citrus fruits and sugarcane, with the Alishang and Alingar rivers as its agricultural lifelines.",
  "AFG:logar": "Province south of Kabul containing the massive Mes Aynak copper deposit, one of the world's largest untapped copper reserves, with a significant ancient Buddhist site.",
  "AFG:kapisa": "Small northeastern province whose capital Mahmud-i-Raqi was historically part of the ancient Kapisha kingdom; known for viticulture and grape production.",
  "AFG:maidan wardak": "Central province directly west of Kabul, strategically important as a Taliban infiltration corridor into the capital throughout the post-2001 conflict.",
  "AFG:bamyan": "Central highland province site of the famous Bamiyan Buddhas, two 6th-century giant statues destroyed by the Taliban in March 2001.",
  "AFG:sar-e pol": "Northern province whose capital Sar-e Pol is known for its traditional felt carpet (gilim) weaving and has a predominantly Uzbek and Hazara population.",
