  "IRN:south khorasan": "Iran's largest province by area, known for saffron cultivation around Birjand and the Lut Desert on its western edge.",
  "IRN:sistan and baluchestan": "Iran's largest province, featuring the ancient Shahr-e Sukhteh (Burnt City) UNESCO site and sharing a long border with Pakistan and Afghanistan.",
  "IRN:bushehr": "Home to Iran's first nuclear power plant at Bushehr city, and a major Persian Gulf port with historic connections to the British East India Company.",
  "IRN:hormozgan": "Contains Bandar Abbas, Iran's busiest port, and the colorful Rainbow Island (Hormuz), known for its vivid mineral-rich red soil and cliffs.",
  "IRN:mazandaran": "Iran's most populous northern province, featuring the Caspian coast, the Alborz mountains, and Mount Damavand, the Middle East's highest peak.",
  "IRN:semnan": "Encompasses part of the Dasht-e Kavir (Great Salt Desert) and is known for Shahroud, as well as the UNESCO-listed Lut Desert on its southeastern edge.",
  "IRN:zanjan": "Known for producing over 70% of Iran's handmade knives (Zanjan knives) and for the Soltaniyeh UNESCO dome, a 14th-century Ilkhanid mausoleum.",
  "IRN:qazvin": "Former Safavid capital city of Qazvin is famed for its Chehel Sotoun palace and serves as a gateway to the Alamut Valley and Assassins' castles.",
  "IRN:markazi": "Capital Arak is Iran's center for heavy industry and machine manufacturing, hosting major petrochemical and rail-manufacturing complexes.",
  "IRN:isfahan": "Naqsh-e Jahan Square in Isfahan, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is one of the largest public squares in the world, flanked by Safavid-era mosques and palaces.",
  "IRN:chaharmahal and bakhtiari": "Source of the Karun River, Iran's only navigable river, and homeland of the Bakhtiari tribe, known for one of the world's great seasonal nomadic migrations.",
  "IRN:kohgiluyeh and boyer-ahmad": "Known for the Dena mountain range and Yasuj as capital; the province is one of Iran's least urbanized, with strong Lur tribal heritage and forest cover.",
  "IRN:fars": "Birthplace of Persian civilization, home to Persepolis — the ancient Achaemenid ceremonial capital and UNESCO World Heritage Site near Shiraz.",
  "IRN:kerman": "Center of Iran's carpet-weaving industry and home to Bam Citadel, the world's largest adobe structure and a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
  "IRN:hamadan": "One of the world's oldest continuously inhabited cities, built on the ancient Median capital Ecbatana, and home to the tomb of the philosopher Avicenna (Ibn Sina).",
  "IRN:lorestan": "Famous for the ancient Luristan bronzes and the historic Falak-ol-Aflak castle in Khorramabad, one of Iran's largest Sassanid-era fortresses.",
  "IRN:yazd": "UNESCO World Heritage city known for its ancient Persian qanat water system, windcatchers (badgirs), and the Zoroastrian Towers of Silence.",
  "IRN:qom": "Iran's holiest city after Mashhad, seat of the country's most influential Shia seminary (hawza), and site of the Fatima Masumeh shrine.",
  "IRN:tehran": "Iran's capital and most populous province, home to over 15 million people and the Golestan Palace, a UNESCO-listed Qajar-era royal complex.",
  "IRN:alborz": "Surrounding the city of Karaj, it hosts Iran's largest dam (Karaj Dam) and is a gateway to ski resorts on the Alborz mountain range near Tehran.",
  // IRQ
